summary:
The Security Council:

Recalling previous resolutions on international terrorism and its threat to Afghanistan, reaffirms its commitment to Afghanistan's sovereignty, independence, territorial integrity, and national unity.

The Council emphasizes its concern about Afghanistan's security situation, including violent activities by the Taliban and associated groups, and terrorist activities by Al-Qaida, ISIL, and their affiliates.

The Council supports a peaceful, stable, and prosperous Afghanistan, and urges an immediate reduction in violence leading to a ceasefire to create an environment conducive to peace negotiations.

The Council reiterates its support for the fight against illicit production and trafficking of drugs and chemical precursors, and recognizes the threats posed by the Taliban, illegal armed groups, and criminals involved in narcotics trade.

The Council welcomes efforts by Afghanistan and the Taliban to facilitate intra-Afghan negotiations and encourages rapid progress on a permanent and comprehensive ceasefire and a political settlement.

Acting under Chapter VII of the Charter, the Council:

1. Decides that all States shall continue measures required by resolution 2255 with respect to individuals and entities designated as the Taliban or associated with it.

2. Decides to continue the 1267/1988 Analytical Support and Sanctions Monitoring Team for 12 months to support the Committee, with the mandate set forth in the annex.

3. Directs the Monitoring Team to gather information on non-compliance, facilitate assistance on capacity-building, and provide recommendations to the Committee.

4. Decides to actively review the implementation of measures outlined in this resolution and consider adjustments as necessary.

5. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
The Monitoring Team shall operate under the direction of the Committee and have the following responsibilities:

(a) Submit an annual comprehensive report to the Committee on implementation by Member States of the measures;

(b) Assist the Committee in reviewing names on the List, including through travel and contact with Member States;

(c) Follow up on requests to Member States for information on implementation of the measures;

(d) Submit a programme of work to the Committee for review and approval;

(e) Gather information on non-compliance with the measures and provide recommendations;

(f) Present recommendations to assist Member States with implementation of the measures;

(g) Assist the Committee in considering proposals for listing;

(h) Bring to the Committee's attention new or noteworthy circumstances for delisting;

(i) Consult with Member States in advance of travel;

(j) Encourage Member States to submit names and information for inclusion on the List;

(k) Consult with the Committee, Government of Afghanistan, or relevant Member States on listing and delisting;

(l) Present additional identifying information to assist the Committee in updating the List;

(m) Collate, assess, monitor and report on implementation of the measures;

(n) Consult with Member States, UNAMA, and other UN agencies;

(o) Cooperate with UNODC and engage in dialogue with Member States and organizations on narcotics trafficking;

(p) Provide an update to the special report of the Monitoring Team;

(q) Consult with Member States' intelligence and security services;

(r) Consult with private sector representatives on the assets freeze;

(s) Cooperate with ISIL and Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee and other counter-terrorism bodies;

(t) Consult with the Government of Afghanistan, Member States, and private sector on sanctions implementation;

(u) Consult with the Government of Afghanistan, Member States, and international organizations on travel ban and assets freeze;

(v) Consult with the Government of Afghanistan, Member States, and international organizations on the threat posed by improvised explosive devices.
The Monitoring Team is tasked with: 

(w) promoting awareness of and compliance with measures through collaboration with international and regional organizations; 

(x) cooperating with INTERPOL and Member States to obtain and exchange information on listed individuals; 

(y) assisting other Security Council subsidiary bodies and expert panels in enhancing cooperation with INTERPOL; 

(z) facilitating assistance in capacity-building for implementing measures upon request by Member States; 

(aa) reporting regularly to the Committee on its work, visits, and activities; 

(bb) studying and reporting on the threat posed by individuals and entities associated with the Taliban and recommending measures to confront it; 

(cc) gathering information on travel exemptions and reporting to the Committee; and 

(dd) undertaking other responsibilities identified by the Committee.
